# Linked List

## Definition

A Linked List is a linear data structure consisting of nodes, where each node stores data and a reference to the next node. Unlike arrays, linked list elements are stored in non-contiguous memory locations.

---

## Node Structure

Each node contains:

- Data
- Reference (Next Pointer)

```
+--------+--------+
| Data   | Next   |
+--------+--------+
```

Example

```
Head
 |
 ▼
10 → 20 → 30 → NULL
```

---

## Components

### Head
- Reference to the first node.
- Starting point for traversal.

### Node
- Basic unit of the linked list.
- Stores data and next node reference.

### Tail
- Last node of the linked list.
- Points to `NULL`.

---

## Memory Representation

```
Address    Data    Next

100        10      250
250        20      500
500        30      NULL
```

Nodes are stored at different memory locations and connected using references.

---

## Characteristics

- Dynamic size
- Non-contiguous memory allocation
- Sequential access
- Efficient insertion and deletion
- Extra memory required for references

---

## Advantages

- Dynamic memory allocation
- Efficient insertion and deletion
- No shifting of elements
- Memory utilization is flexible

---

## Disadvantages

- No direct indexing
- Sequential traversal
- Additional memory for references
- Poor cache locality compared to arrays

---

## Applications

- Music Playlist
- Browser History
- Undo / Redo
- Image Viewer
- Graph Adjacency List
- Hash Table Chaining

---

## Time Complexity

| Operation | Complexity |
|-----------|------------|
| Access | O(n) |
| Search | O(n) |
| Traversal | O(n) |
| Insert at Beginning | O(1) |
| Insert at End | O(n) |
| Delete at Beginning | O(1) |
| Delete at End | O(n) |

> Insert at End becomes **O(1)** if a tail pointer is maintained.

---

## Space Complexity

- Overall: **O(n)**
- Per Node: **O(1)**

---

## Array vs Linked List

| Feature | Array | Linked List |
|---------|-------|-------------|
| Memory | Contiguous | Non-contiguous |
| Size | Fixed | Dynamic |
| Random Access | O(1) | O(n) |
| Insertion | O(n) | O(1) after traversal |
| Deletion | O(n) | O(1) after traversal |
| Extra Memory | No | Yes |

---

## Key Points

- Nodes are connected using references.
- The first node is called the Head.
- The last node points to NULL.
- Linked Lists support dynamic memory allocation.
- Searching requires sequential traversal.

